Response:  We know that there are 32 muangams in one hour. So, if we divide the total number of hours (15) by the number of muangams per hour (32), we get the answer as follows:

Number of muangamis in 15 hours = 15 x 32 = 480
Therefore, out of 32 muangamis, 480 muangamis will be left after 15 hours.;

Response:  We know that there are 41 days in April and May combined (April has 30 days and May has 5 days). So, if we want to find out how many people who were 18 years old in April will turn 19 in May, we need to multiply 41 by 0.07 (which is the proportion of people who turn 19 in May among those who were 18 in April). Therefore, the number of people who will turn 19 in May is:

$$ \boxed{41 \times 0.07 = 2.87} $$
So, approximately 2.87 people will turn 19 in May for every 100 people who were 18 years old in April.;

Response:  We know that there are 10 cups of water in the container initially and after pouring 45 ml of milk into it, there were 11 cups of water left. So, we can calculate the amount of milk added as follows:
Milk added = Total volume of milk / Volume of water remaining = 45 ml / 11 cups = 4 ml
So, there are 4 ml of milk added to the initial 10 cups of water.;

